Rating: 4
This recipe does indeed make enough for a dozen but my family of 3 loved it so much we barely got two meals out of it! I didn't have smoked ham hocks but I did have the remnants of a baked ham. I boiled it for hours w/onions, celery, etc., cooled, skimmed fat and got lots of chunky ham for the soup. I used the ham broth instead of chicken broth and added a little white wine. After I'd spent all that time preparing, I realized I was out of potatoes. But I was NOT out of rutabegas, so I cut up half a big rutabega and tossed that in (figured since both are root veggies it's okay to substitute!). The peppery rutabegas were PERFECT for this hardy soup and really made it special. I put in 1/2 c barley on the first go 'round and added another 1/2 c on the reheat. Next time I make it I think I'll reduce the amount of carrots (the carrot taste overshadowed the others a little bit) and increase the rutabegas!

Rating: 4
One of the best soup recipes I've found. The oregano adds a distinct flavor I hadn't expected. I believe the symbol in front of Barley stands for scant. This could easily be increased to 1½ cups of barley, as currently there are only about two pieces in each spoon full. I advise adding the barley with the ham and increasing the simmer time to 45 min. Then, after adding the rest of the ingredients, reduce remaining simmer time by 15 minutes to 45 minutes. There is enough soup to easily feed 12 so half the recipe or plan on freezing some.

